The '''1998 FA Charity Shield''' (also known as the '''AXA FA Charity Shield''' for sponsorship reasons) was the 76th [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]], an annual English [[association football|football]] match organised by [[The Football Association]] and played between the winners of the previous season's [[Premier League]] and [[FA Cup]] competitions. It was contested on 9 August 1998 by [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] <U+2013> who won a [[1997<U+2013>98 FA Premier League|league]] and [[1997<U+2013>98 FA Cup|FA Cup]] [[Double (association football)|double]] the previous season <U+2013> and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] <U+2013> who finished runners-up in the league. Watched by a crowd of 67,342 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], Arsenal won the match 3<U+2013>0.

This was Manchester United's 18th Charity Shield appearance to Arsenal's 14th. Manchester United began the game more strongly, but Arsenal took the lead when [[Marc Overmars]] scored 11 minutes before half-time. They extended their lead in the second half, as Overmars and [[Nicolas Anelka]] found [[Christopher Wreh]], who put the ball into an empty net at the second attempt. In the 72nd minute, Arsenal scored a third goal, when Anelka got around [[Jaap Stam]] in the penalty box and shot the ball past goalkeeper [[Peter Schmeichel]].

Arsenal's victory marked Manchester United's first Shield defeat in 13 years. The teams later faced each other in the [[1998<U+2013>99 FA Cup#Semi-finals|FA Cup semi-final]], which was won by Manchester United in a replay. Manchester United finished the league season one point ahead of Arsenal and went on to win the FA Cup and [[1998<U+2013>99 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], thereby completing a [[Treble (association football)|treble]] of trophies in the [[1998<U+2013>99 in English football|1998<U+2013>99]] season.

==Background==
[[File:Wembleyold.jpg|thumb|[[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] played host to the Charity Shield for the 25th time.]]
Founded in 1908 as a successor to the [[Sheriff of London Charity Shield]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Abandonment of the Sheriff Shield |page=11 |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=19 April 1908 }}</ref> the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] began as a contest between the respective champions of the [[The Football League|Football League]] and [[Southern Football League|Southern League]], although in 1913 it was played between an Amateurs XI and a Professionals XI.<ref>{{cite news |title=The F.A. Charity Shield |page=10 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=7 October 1913 }}</ref> In 1921, it was played by the league champions of the top division and [[FA Cup]] winners for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Ferguson |title=The FA Community Shield history |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/news/team-news/archive/2011/august/community-shield-2011/the-shield-from-the-beginning |publisher=mcfc.co.uk (Manchester City FC) |date=4 August 2011 |accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The [[Premier League]] replaced the [[Football League First Division]] at the top of the [[English football league system|English football pyramid]] after its inception in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |title=Continental or the full English? |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/dec/02/sport.sportfeatures |first=Alex |last=Fynn |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=2 December 2001 |accessdate=3 July 2014 }}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} The match was played at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], which first hosted the Shield in 1974.<ref>{{cite news |title=The FA Community Shield history |url=http://www.thefa.com/fa-community-shield/more/history |publisher=TheFA.com (The Football Association) |accessdate=3 July 2013 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Hthw8Bhx |archivedate=5 July 2013 |deadurl=no }}</ref>

[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] qualified for the 1998 FA Charity Shield as winners of the [[1997<U+2013>98 FA Premier League]].<ref name="rule">{{cite news |title=Arsenal soon back in the groove |page=48 |newspaper=Courier Mail |location=Queensland |date=10 August 1998 }}</ref> Although they were 12 points behind league leaders [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] by the end of February 1998, a nine-match winning streak, culminating in a 4<U+2013>0 win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 3 May 1998, ensured Arsenal won the title.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Lacey |title=Gunners rest their case for the defence |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=4 May 1998 |page=A3 }}</ref> Arsenal beat [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] 2<U+2013>0 in the [[1998 FA Cup Final]] to complete the [[Double (association football)|domestic double]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal at the double |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/94885.stm |publisher=BBC News (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=16 May 1998 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> Given they won both honours, the other Charity Shield place went to league runners-up Manchester United.<ref name="rule"/>

The most recent meeting between the two teams was in the Premier League on 14 March 1998, when a second-half goal by [[Marc Overmars]] gave Arsenal a 1<U+2013>0 win at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal v Manchester United head-to-head record |url=http://www.manchesterunited-mad.co.uk/head_to_head/arsenal/vs/manchester_united/index.shtml |work=United Mad |publisher=Digital Sports Group |accessdate=3 July 2013 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6HthfWHaK |archivedate=5 July 2013 |deadurl=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Overmars keeps title race alive |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/65594.stm |publisher=BBC News (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=14 March 1998 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> Arsenal were the only team in the 1997<U+2013>98 league to beat United home and away, with the corresponding home fixture ending 3<U+2013>2.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester United <U+2013> 1997<U+2013>98 |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/manchester-united/1997-1998 |publisher=Statto Organisation |accessdate=3 July 2013 }}</ref> Arsenal manager [[Ars<U+00E8>ne Wenger]] acknowledged the Shield game was the "only opportunity to play our first-team men together against top-class opposition" before their league campaign commenced the following week.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Hart |title=Arsenal need spirit to cure the hangover |page=71 |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=7 August 1998 }}</ref> Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] was preoccupied with the team's match against [[<U+0141>KS <U+0141><U+00F3>d<U+017A>]] in the [[1998<U+2013>99 UEFA Champions League#Second qualifying round|second qualifying round]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]] three days later. He felt the contest with Arsenal would get his "players' sharpness up and provide plenty of benefit" for their upcoming matches.<ref>{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Cass |title=Keane to succeed |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-110696631.html |newspaper=The Mail on Sunday |location=London |date=10 August 1998}} {{subscription required}}</ref>

The match was officially referred to as "The AXA FA Charity Shield" as part of a sponsorship deal between [[The Football Association]] and French insurance group [[AXA]], agreed in July 1998. The deal also saw the FA Cup referred to as "The AXA Sponsored FA Cup" for its four-year duration.<ref>{{cite news |title=F.A. Gets Four Year AXA Sponsorship |url=http://mediatel.co.uk/newsline/1998/07/23/f-a-gets-four-year-axa-sponsorship/ |work=Newsline |publisher=Mediatel Group |date=23 July 1998 |accessdate=17 June 2014 }}</ref>

==Match==
===Team selection===
Manchester United winger [[Jesper Blomqvist]] was ruled out with an ankle injury, but [[Roy Keane]] was fit enough to start his first competitive match since damaging his ligaments eleven months previously.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jon |last=Brodkin |title=Blomqvist out as Keane eyes return |page=B6 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 August 1998 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Millar |title=Keane can't wait for the sparks to fly |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Keane+can%27t+wait+for+the+sparks+to+fly.-a060662997 |newspaper=The Mirror |location=London |date=12 August 1998 |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Defender [[Jaap Stam]], who signed for United in May 1998,<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Maddock |title=Stam's arrival relieves the gloom for United |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=6 May 1998 |page=41 }}</ref> made his competitive debut for the club, partnering centre-back [[Ronny Johnsen]].<ref name="report"/> For Arsenal, new signing [[Nelson Vivas]] began the match on the substitutes' bench,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wenger is gunning for domestic success |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/wenger-is-gunning-for-domestic-success-1.331884 |newspaper=The Herald |location=Glasgow |date=17 August 1998 |accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref> in spite of being expected to make his full debut,<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Martin |title=Charity and faith is Vivas' hope |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-charity-and-faith-is-vivas-hope-1170601.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=9 August 1998 |accessdate=16 February 2013}}</ref> while [[Dennis Bergkamp]] started alongside [[Nicolas Anelka]] up front.<ref name="str">{{cite news |last=Dillon |first=John |title=Wenger's hot shots have fun in the sun; Arsenal 3 Man Utd 0 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/WENGER%27S+HOT+SHOTS+HAVE+FUN+IN+THE+SUN%3b+Arsenal+3+Man+Utd+0.-a060665399 |newspaper=The Mirror |location=London |date=10 August 1998 |accessdate=16 February 2013 }}</ref>

Arsenal employed a traditional [[Formation (association football)#4<U+2013>4<U+2013>2|4<U+2013>4<U+2013>2]] formation: a four-man [[Defender (association football)|defence]] (comprising two [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-backs]] and [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left and right full-backs]]), four [[midfielders]] (two in the [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|centre]], and one on each [[Midfielders#Wide midfielder|wing]]) and two [[Forward (association football)#Centre forward|centre-forwards]].<ref name="guard">{{cite news |first=David |last=Lacey |title=Wenger's all-stars write an epitaph to United; FA Charity Shield Arsenal 3 Manchester United 0: Overmars sets Double winners on way to victory that promises more success |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=10 August 1998 |page=21}}</ref> Manchester United organised themselves slightly differently, with [[Paul Scholes]] playing ahead of the midfield in a supporting role behind the main striker, [[Andy Cole]]. The team lined up in a [[Formation (association football)#4<U+2013>4<U+2013>1<U+2013>1|4<U+2013>4<U+2013>1<U+2013>1]] formation.<ref name="guard"/>

===Summary===
In pitch-side temperatures of {{convert|30|<U+00B0>C|<U+00B0>F}},<ref name="reporttwo"/> Manchester United enjoyed their best spell of the match early on, while Arsenal's pair [[Patrick Vieira]] and [[Emmanuel Petit]] adjusted themselves.<ref name="guard"/> United fashioned their first chance through [[David Beckham]], who was booed throughout the match on account of many fans blaming him for [[England national football team|England]]'s elimination from the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name="guard"/>{{#tag:ref|Beckham was [[Red card (association football)#Red card (dismissal)|sent off]] for kicking [[Diego Simeone]] in the second round of the 1998 World Cup against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]. His dismissal led to considerable abuse from certain sections of the media and England fans. The player became a scapegoat for the national team's failure to progress, as in the match England were eliminated on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Dave |last=Hill |title=Beckham |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/beckham-1171687.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=15 August 1998 |accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} His pass eventually met Scholes, whose attempt forced Arsenal goalkeeper [[David Seaman]] to clear.<ref name="report">{{cite news |first=Oliver |last=Holt |title=Arsenal warm to their second home |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=10 August 1998 |page=32 }}</ref> In spite of United's promising start, it was Arsenal who scored the opening goal. Vieira played the ball down the right side of the penalty area in the direction of Bergkamp and Anelka. Bergkamp got there first and back-heeled the ball to Anelka, but the Frenchman was unable to take control; however, he was able to put pressure on Johnsen in the Manchester United defence and blocked the Norwegian's attempted clearance. The ball ran across the edge of the penalty area to Overmars, who lashed it right-footed past Manchester United goalkeeper [[Peter Schmeichel]] into the net.<ref name="report"/> A shot by Keane from {{convert|25|yd}} prompted a save from Seaman in the 42nd minute.<ref name="reporttwo"/>

Arsenal began dominating in the second half, and increased their lead after 57 minutes. From the left wing, Overmars used his pace to get the better of [[Gary Neville]] and passed the ball to Anelka, who turned and passed to an unmarked [[Christopher Wreh]]. Schmeichel blocked the Liberian's initial shot with his feet, but he was unable to stop the second attempt or Wreh's acrobatic celebration.<ref name="reporttwo"/> Despite the setback, United continued to press Arsenal; defender [[Martin Keown]] almost put the ball into his own goal from [[Ryan Giggs]]'s corner.<ref name="reporttwo"/> Both teams made mass substitutions in the final third of the game, notably [[Teddy Sheringham]] and [[Lu<U+00ED>s Boa Morte]] coming on for Cole <U+2013> who rarely threatened <U+2013> and Petit, respectively.<ref name="report"/> Arsenal scored their third in the 72nd minute <U+2013> Parlour's pass found Anelka, who got around Stam and shot the ball past Schmeichel from a narrow angle, inside the goalkeeper's near post.<ref name="report"/> Near the end, Sheringham wasted a goal-scoring opportunity, shooting wide.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boo-boy Beckham fails to paper over Ferguson's cracks |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Boo-boy+Beckham+fails+to+paper+over+Ferguson%27s+cracks%3b+Arsenal+3...-a061434512 |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=10 August 1998}}</ref>

