==Post-match==
[[File:Arsene Wenger.JPG|thumb|upright|left|[[Ars<U+00E8>ne Wenger]] was surprised by Arsenal's margin of victory.]]
The result marked Manchester United's first Shield defeat in 13 years,<ref name="reporttwo"/> and was the ninth time Arsenal had won the Charity Shield.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Ross |title=List of FA Charity/Community Shield Matches |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsupcuphist.html |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF) |date=15 August 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2014 }}</ref> Arsenal became the first southern club{{#tag:ref|One which is located in the southern [[counties]] of England. Initially these were amateur clubs, as professionalism in football was not as readily accepted in the south as in the north. In the 1893<U+2013>94 season, Arsenal (under its former name Woolwich Arsenal) turned professional and became the first southern club admitted to the northern-oriented [[The Football League|Football League]]. The following year saw the creation of the [[Southern Football League]], which was composed of amateur and professional teams. By the [[1920<U+2013>21 in English football|1920<U+2013>21]] season, the top division of the Southern Football League was absorbed by the Football League, to create its third division.<ref>{{cite book |first=Alan |last=Tomlinson |title=A Dictionary of Sports Studies |url=http://books.google.com/?id=r_Ujf9-TmBUC&pg=PA196 |page=196 |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2010 |isbn=0-19-921381-X }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=1895: Drama, Disaster and Disgrace in Late Victorian Britain |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vYhvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT39 |page=39 |first=Nicholas |last=Freeman |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |year=2011 |isbn=0-7486-4056-8 }}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} since [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in [[1962 FA Charity Shield|1962]] to win the Shield outright.<ref name="reporttwo"/> Wenger described the scoreline as "unexpected" and cited the first goal as crucial in the match, given the weather conditions.<ref>{{cite news |first=Philip |last=Dorward |title=Charity Shield victory gives Arsenal important psychological edge over Old Trafford rivals |newspaper=The Scotsman |location=Edinburgh |date=10 August 1998 |page=21 }}</ref><ref name="wenger">{{cite news |first=Martin |last=Lipton |title=Fans will make it hell for Beckham |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-110696499.html |newspaper=Daily Mail |location=London |date=10 August 1998}} {{subscription required}}</ref> He was content with how his international players, who had been in the World Cup, coped with the game's physicality. Wenger believed the result gave Arsenal a psychological boost for the Champions League campaign, as the club planned to stage their home matches at Wembley Stadium.<ref name="wenger"/> Bergkamp felt the result showed that Arsenal had what it took to retain the Premier League title: "We've still got the same mentality and that will be the basis for this year's challenge. This is a good start. It is harder to retain the trophy."<ref name="wenger"/>

Ferguson admitted his team had been beaten by the better side and agreed with Wenger that the first goal was important.<ref name="fergie"/><ref name="report"/> He was pleased that Keane got through the match after 11 months out of action and was confident his team would fare better against <U+0141>KS <U+0141><U+00F3>d<U+017A>, the following Wednesday.<ref name="fergie">{{cite news |title=Arsene approves of that Wembley winning habit |page=32 |newspaper=Herald Express |location=Torquay |date=10 August 1998 }}</ref> Schmeichel felt the upcoming Champions League qualifier was more important than the Charity Shield game, which he considered as a pre-season match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man U on new ground in early cup clash |page=25 |newspaper=Hobart Mercury |date=12 August 1998 }}</ref> Ferguson anticipated another challenge from Arsenal in the league: "I think you could make a strong case for four teams to challenge for the Premiership but I think Arsenal pose the biggest threat."<ref name="fergie"/>

Three days after the Charity Shield match, United beat <U+0141>KS <U+0141><U+00F3>d<U+017A> 2<U+2013>0 and qualified for the Champions League group stage following a goalless match a fortnight later.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Mark |last=Pierson |title=Roving role is fine by Giggs |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-roving-role-is-fine-by-giggs-1171585.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=14 August 1998 |accessdate=3 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Guy |last=Hodgson |title=United poles apart from Lodz |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-united-poles-apart-from-lodz-1174436.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=27 August 1998 |accessdate=3 July 2013 }}</ref> Arsenal had the upper hand in their two league meetings with United during the season, winning 3<U+2013>0 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] in September 1998,<ref>{{cite news |first=Henry |last=Winter |title=Fergie shell-shocked by awesome Gunners |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/fergie-shellshocked-by-awesome-gunners-433473.html |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=21 September 1998 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> before a 1<U+2013>1 draw at Old Trafford in February 1999.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Guy |last=Hodgson |title=United rescued by Cole |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-united-rescued-by-cole-1071629.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=18 February 1999 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> The two teams went into the final day of the [[1998<U+2013>99 FA Premier League]] vying for the title, but United's 2<U+2013>1 win against Tottenham meant they finished one point above Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Oliver |last1=Holt |first2=Matt |last2=Dickinson |title=One down, two to go for United |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=17 May 1999 |page=25 }}</ref> The two sides met twice more that season in the FA Cup semi-final, which was settled in a replay after the original match finished goalless.<ref>{{cite news |first=Oliver |last=Holt |title=Odds grow longer on treble chance |page=29 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=12 April 1999 }}</ref> Manchester United won in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] <U+2013> the winning goal scored by Giggs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Giggs magic sinks Gunners |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_cup/319696.stm |publisher=BBC News (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=14 April 1999 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> United then went on to defeat Newcastle United 2<U+2013>0 in the [[1999 FA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Double joy for United |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_cup/350192.stm |publisher=BBC News (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=22 May 1999 |accessdate=23 May 2014 }}</ref> Whereas Arsenal failed to progress past the group stage of the Champions League,<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Tongue |title=Parlour off as Arsenal go out |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-parlour-off-as-arsenal-go-out-1187462.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=26 November 1998 |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Manchester United went on to reach the [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final|final]], where they beat [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] to win the competition for the second time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Treble joy for United fans |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/353844.stm |publisher=BBC News (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=27 May 1999 |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Ferguson's team therefore completed a [[Treble (association football)|treble]] of trophies in one season.<ref>{{cite news |title=United crowned kings of Europe |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/353842.stm |publisher=BBC News (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=26 May 1999 |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>

